<section class="intro-section mb-12">
  <h3 id="mission">Mission</h3>
  <p>
    <strong>Web Workflows</strong> standardizes a <strong>workflow</strong> &mdash; a set of smaller UX
    intents arranged in <strong>directed progression toward one goal</strong>
    (<code>checkout = collect-address &rarr; pay &rarr; confirm</code>), with threaded state, a single
    completion criterion, and one current position. It is the missing <strong>third composition
    mode</strong>: Web Everything already has <em>simultaneous</em> composition (a block composes intents
    that all act at once) and <em>cross-cutting</em> composition (one intent's policy reused across blocks),
    but neither expresses <em>directed/temporal</em> composition &mdash; step-intents progressing toward a
    terminal goal with threaded state.
  </p>
  <p>
    Web Workflows fixes one seam &mdash; a <strong>declarative orchestration graph</strong> (steps +
    transitions + guards + parallel/fork-join + completion) resolved by a swappable
    <strong>workflow engine</strong> &mdash; and nothing else. The graph is data, so a workflow engine
    (XState, SCION, a hand-rolled switch) plugs in behind the provider without touching the step-intents,
    which compose into the flow unaware they are in one. <strong>The transition graph is the only
    lock.</strong>
  </p>

  <div class="comparison-block" style="background: rgba(14, 165, 233, 0.08); padding: 1.25rem; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid #0ea5e9; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
    <h4 style="margin-top: 0; color: #0369a1; font-size: 1rem;">Sibling of Web Lifecycle, not the same thing</h4>
    <p style="margin-bottom: 0; font-size: 0.95rem;">
      <a href="/projects/weblifecycle/">Web Lifecycle</a> owns a <em>persisted domain entity's</em> status
      &mdash; an FSM in one state at a time (a loan is <code>underwriting</code>), whose event is an audit
      trail. Web Workflows owns the <em>user's ephemeral traversal</em> &mdash; a process orchestration that
      may occupy <em>many</em> states at once (parallel branches), whose event is back/undo navigation. Same
      SCXML transition-map <em>form</em>, different subject, cardinality, and event semantics. They are
      siblings over a shared form, not one protocol &mdash; bias-to-separation
      (<a href="/backlog/634-meta-intent-workflow-as-composable-intent/">#634</a>,
      <a href="/backlog/616-retroactively-ratify-the-weblifecycle-project-lifecycle-prot/">#616</a>).
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

