<section id="protocol-workflow" class="section-card">
  <h3 id="how-it-works">Workflow Protocol</h3>
  <p>
    A flow never bundles its orchestration into the step-intents. It declares a <strong>workflow
    definition</strong> (steps + transition graph + completion), resolves the application's
    <strong>workflow engine</strong> through the injector chain, and asks it to advance. The engine
    evaluates the edge's guard (delegating authorization to a guard provider), threads context, applies the
    move, and emits the step-transition event. The protocol fixes only the seam &mdash; the engine behind
    the provider is swappable.
  </p>
  {% highlight "typescript" %}
// The orchestration graph — the ONLY lock. Data-defined (SCXML-style), portable across engines.
interface WorkflowDefinition<S extends string> {
  initial: S;
  steps: Record<S, { final?: boolean; parallel?: S[] }>;   // `final` = a completion state
  transitions: Array<{
    from: S; to: S;
    // Authorization is NOT owned here — `guard` names a Web Guards predicate the
    // CustomGuardProvider resolves (async, server-authoritative). Omit for a free move.
    guard?: string;
    // The operator producing this edge (Tier-1 sequence/branch/nest, Tier-2 back/parallel/gate).
    op?: 'sequence' | 'branch' | 'nest' | 'parallel' | 'back' | 'gate';
  }>;
}

// The provider seam — satisfied by the native default and every plugged engine alike.
interface CustomWorkflowEngine<S extends string = string> {
  // Which transitions are available from the current position(s), guards pre-evaluated.
  available(flow: FlowRef, actor: ActorRef): Promise<S[]>;
  // Advance one edge. Rejects if unknown or its guard denies. On success, emits the event.
  advance(flow: FlowRef, to: S, actor: ActorRef): Promise<StepTransitionEvent<S>>;
  // Has the flow reached a completion (`final`) state?
  isComplete(flow: FlowRef): boolean;
}

interface StepTransitionEvent<S extends string> {
  flow: FlowRef; from: S; to: S; context: unknown; at: string; // ISO
}

// 1. The application registers ONE engine (native-first default; project overrides it).
customWorkflows.define('checkout', new XStateWorkflowEngine(checkoutDefinition));

injector Application {
  provide { workflow: 'checkout' } to '@web-workflows';   // every descendant resolves this engine
}

// 2. A surface delegates — it owns neither the graph nor the authorization.
const engine = InjectorRoot.getProviderOf(el, 'customWorkflows');
const next = await engine.available(checkout, currentUser);   // → ['pay', 'edit-address']
const ev = await engine.advance(checkout, 'pay', currentUser); // guard-checked + context-threaded
  {% endhighlight %}

  <h4 id="operators" style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">Operator vocabulary (tiered, open meta-schema)</h4>
  <p>
    The standardized operator set is <strong>tiered by universality</strong> and stays an
    <strong>open meta-schema</strong> &mdash; engines declare <em>which</em> operators they honor (the
    <a href="/backlog/085-validation-adapters-multi-language/">#085</a> compliance-matrix posture). Tier-3
    is recorded here, not dropped, so promoting an operator later is a status flip, not a re-survey.
  </p>
  <div style="overflow-x: auto; max-width: 100%;">
    <table style="min-width: 720px;">
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Tier</th><th>Operators</th><th>Why here</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td><strong>Tier-1 &mdash; core (mandatory)</strong></td><td>sequence · branch/guard · nest (sub-workflow) · threaded context · completion/final · current-position</td><td>The coherence invariant &mdash; what makes a workflow a workflow rather than co-located intents.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Tier-2 &mdash; common (optional)</strong></td><td>parallel fork/join · back/undo · gate/wait-for-event</td><td>Recurs across surveyed systems &amp; UI wizards; optional, not structural.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Tier-3 &mdash; deferred (known, not standardized)</strong></td><td>fan-out/matrix · inclusive-OR · history/resume · retry · compensation/saga</td><td>Redundant via existing primitives (matrix &rarr; parallel; inclusive-OR &rarr; parallel + per-branch guards) or durable-execution <em>backend</em> concerns that belong to the engine behind the provider, never the contract.</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <ul style="font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--color-text-muted); margin-top: 1rem;">
    <li><strong>One contract:</strong> <code>CustomWorkflowEngine</code> &mdash;
      <code>available()</code> + <code>advance()</code> + <code>isComplete()</code> &mdash; is satisfied by
      the default and every plugged engine alike.</li>
    <li><strong>One registry:</strong> <code>CustomWorkflowRegistry</code>
      (<code>window.customWorkflows</code>) holds the named definitions/engines; the project selects or
      overrides via the injector chain.</li>
    <li><strong>Authorization is delegated, never re-implemented:</strong> a transition's
      <code>guard</code> is a <a href="/projects/webguards/">Web Guards</a> predicate &mdash; Web Workflows
      owns <em>the graph</em>; Web Guards owns <em>who may advance an edge</em>.</li>
    <li><strong>Every transition is observable:</strong> the emitted <code>StepTransitionEvent</code> is the
      composition seam for the <a href="/intents/flow-progress/">Flow Progress intent</a>, audit, and
      reporting &mdash; the standard owns the event, not the log.</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section id="composition" class="section-card">
  <h3 id="composition">Composition With Other Standards</h3>
  <ul style="font-size: 0.9rem;">
    <li><strong><a href="/intents/flow-progress/">Flow Progress intent</a></strong> &mdash; the UX half: the
      current position, per-step status, and register (wizard / single-page / conversational / board). It
      reads the same engine; it is the workflow's visual member.</li>
    <li><strong><a href="/projects/weblifecycle/">Web Lifecycle</a></strong> &mdash; the sibling: a persisted
      entity's FSM status (one state, audit event) vs a workflow's ephemeral traversal (may be many states,
      back/undo event). Shared SCXML form, separate protocols.</li>
    <li><strong><a href="/intents/navigation/">Navigation intent</a></strong> &mdash; the Flow Progress
      intent reuses its <code>structure:linear</code> / <code>guard</code> / <code>history</code> dimensions
      rather than reinventing linear movement.</li>
    <li><strong><a href="/projects/webguards/">Web Guards</a></strong> &mdash; resolves each transition's
      guard predicate (authorization / precondition).</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section id="status" class="section-card">
  <h3 id="status">Status</h3>
  <p>
    Web Workflows is in <strong>concept</strong> phase; the Workflow protocol's seam (orchestration graph +
    engine provider + step-transition event) is specified here at <strong>draft</strong>, and the
    <a href="/intents/flow-progress/">Flow Progress intent</a> carries the UX. It was ratified by
    <a href="/backlog/634-meta-intent-workflow-as-composable-intent/">#634</a> (Fork 1 = A: Project +
    Protocol + Intent decomposition; Fork 2 = A: tiered operators, open meta-schema), grounded in the
    workflow meta-intent survey (<a href="/research/workflow-meta-intent/">/research/workflow-meta-intent/</a>).
    It subsumes the collection-operations coordinator
    (<a href="/backlog/369-collection-operations-coordinator/">#369</a>) as a degenerate co-located instance.
    The native-first default engine adapter and a reference wizard block are the first planned work, on top
    of this contract &mdash; filed as separately-prioritized builds.
  </p>
</section>
